<subsection><title>Wrap-Up</title>
<p>In this Lesson, we worked on the following skills and goals related to algebraic fractions:</p>
<p><ul>
<li><p>Simplify complex fractions</p></li>    
<li><p>Simplify expressions involving negative exponents</p></li>    
<li><p>Use polynomial division to simplify fractions</p></li>
</ul></p>

<commentary audience="instructor"><title>Questions for Writing or Discussion</title>
<p><ol>
<li><p>Compare the procedure for simplifying a complex fraction to the procedure for adding unlike fractions.</p></li>
<li><p>How should you write the numerator of a fraction before starting polynomial division?</p></li>
<li><p>Explain why it makes sense that <m>\dfrac{23}{5} = 4\dfrac{3}{5}</m>.</p></li>
<li><p>Suppose you drive 60 miles at 40 mph, and then drive another 60 miles at 60 mph. How long did it take you? What was your average speed? Explain your reasoning at each step.</p></li>
</ol></p></commentary>
</subsection> 

